 that assume that Japanese literary modernity began with Tsubouchi Shōyō's The Essence of the Novel (1885-6). This view has long confined the discussion of literature to very narrow terms. By recasting the Shōyō's work in the political and intellectual domains, Concealment of Politics, Politics of Concealment not only explores the interaction of different discourses in 1880s Japan but offers a rigorous critique of our own approaches to the history of modern Japanese literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362689840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626898/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles